[recv] {"method":"item/completed","params":{"item":{"type":"agentMessage","id":"msg_0259c20ac2af89bc0169c54ea1048081918dff362013f9674f","text":"Created the minimal RP2040 breakout in [index.circuit.tsx](/workspace/index.circuit.tsx), using JLCPCB-imported RP2040, USB-C, regulator, flash, crystal, and LED parts from [imports/RP2040.tsx](/workspace/imports/RP2040.tsx), [imports/TYPE_C_16PIN_2MD_073_.tsx](/workspace/imports/TYPE_C_16PIN_2MD_073_.tsx), [imports/ME6211C33M5G_N.tsx](/workspace/imports/ME6211C33M5G_N.tsx), [imports/W25Q16JVUXIQ.tsx](/workspace/imports/W25Q16JVUXIQ.tsx), [imports/X322512MSB4SI.tsx](/workspace/imports/X322512MSB4SI.tsx), and [imports/XL_1608SYGC_06.tsx](/workspace/imports/XL_1608SYGC_06.tsx). The board includes USB power/data, 3.3 V regulation, QSPI flash, 12 MHz crystal, a GPIO25 status LED, two 15-pin GPIO breakout headers, and a 6-pin utility header for `3V3`, `GND`, `VBUS`, `RUN`, `SWD`, and `SWCLK`.\n\nValidation status: `tsci check netlist` passes cleanly, and `tsci build` completes and writes [dist/index/circuit.json](/workspace/dist/index/circuit.json). The remaining issue is PCB autorouting: the current layout still leaves 5 unresolved routing nodes in the autorouter, so the design is electrically defined and buildable but not fully auto-routed yet. I also patched the imported RP2040 footprint in [imports/RP2040.tsx](/workspace/imports/RP2040.tsx) to remove an invalid scientific-notation pad coordinate that was causing build warnings.\n\nIf you want, I can do one more pass focused only on reducing the unrouted nets.","phase":"final_answer","memoryCitation":null},"threadId":"019d2ab0-6a23-7151-90d2-d0c7efabb658","turnId":"019d2ab0-6a28-7873-9dfd-567119e7219e"}}
